<h2>The 2025 Tools Landscape: What Changed</h2>

<p>
  Looking back at 2025 from our vantage point in 2026, several trends defined the year in developer tools:
</p>

<p>
  <strong>WebAssembly went mainstream.</strong> Tools that previously required server-side processing — like code compilation, image optimization, and heavy data transformations — moved entirely to the browser thanks to WASM. This meant faster execution, better privacy, and zero server costs for tool providers.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>AI became a feature, not a product.</strong> Instead of standalone AI tools, intelligence was embedded into existing developer tools. JSON formatters gained AI-powered error correction. Regex testers added natural language pattern descriptions. Code formatters learned to detect and apply project-specific style conventions. The AI was most useful when it was invisible.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Privacy became non-negotiable.</strong> High-profile data breaches involving developer tools (leaked API keys, exposed JWT tokens, scraped code snippets) pushed the industry toward client-side processing. Developers in 2025 started demanding proof that their data never leaves the browser, and tools that could not provide that guarantee lost users rapidly.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Mobile-first development tools emerged.</strong> With more developers working from tablets and phones (for quick fixes, code reviews, and on-call debugging), tools that worked well on mobile screens gained significant traction. Responsive design for developer tools was no longer a nice-to-have.
</p>

