<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>Are free developer tools safe to use with sensitive data?</h3>

<p>
  Yes, when they process data entirely in your browser (client-side). Tools that use JavaScript and WebAssembly to transform data never send your input to a server. Always check a tool's privacy policy and look for "client-side only" or "no server processing" claims. All tools on DevToolkit process data locally in your browser — your code, tokens, and passwords never leave your machine.
</p>

<h3>Can free tools replace paid developer software?</h3>

<p>
  For individual utility tasks — formatting, encoding, hashing, generating — absolutely. Free browser tools handle these tasks as well as or better than paid alternatives. Where paid tools still excel is in team collaboration features, enterprise SSO integration, audit logs, and advanced workflow automation. For the vast majority of daily development tasks, free tools are more than sufficient.
</p>

<h3>Do these 2025 tools still work in 2026?</h3>

<p>
  Yes. Browser-based tools that use standard web APIs (like the Web Crypto API for hashing, or TextEncoder for encoding) continue to work as long as browsers support those APIs — which is indefinitely, since they are part of web standards. The tools listed in this article are all actively maintained and receive regular updates.
</p>

<h3>What is the difference between a code formatter and a code minifier?</h3>

<p>
  A formatter makes code human-readable by adding whitespace, indentation, and line breaks. A minifier does the opposite — it removes all unnecessary whitespace, shortens variable names, and strips comments to reduce file size. Formatters are for development (readability and debugging). Minifiers are for production (performance and bandwidth). You typically format during development and minify before deployment.
</p>

<h3>How many tokens does a typical API prompt use?</h3>

<p>
  It varies significantly by content type and model. As a rough guide: 1 token is approximately 4 characters or 0.75 words in English. A 500-word prompt uses roughly 670 tokens. Code is less token-efficient than natural language — a 100-line JavaScript function might use 800-1200 tokens. Non-English text, especially CJK characters, can use 2-3x more tokens per character. Use a <a href="/tools/token-counter">Token Counter</a> for precise measurements with your specific model.
</p>

<h3>Why should I use a unified toolkit instead of separate tool websites?</h3>

<p>
  Three reasons: consistency, speed, and trust. A unified toolkit means one interface to learn, one set of keyboard shortcuts, and one privacy policy to verify. You spend less time context-switching between different UIs and more time on actual development. Plus, a single maintained platform is more likely to keep its tools updated and secure than a random collection of one-off tool sites found through search results.
</p>

